Position embedding methods
RoPE (Su et al., 2021) applies a rotation to query and key vectors based on absolute position. Each pair of dimensions in the head is rotated by \(\theta_i \cdot t\) where \(t\) is the position index and \(\theta_i\) is a frequency drawn from a geometric series up to rope_max_timescale. The rotation makes the dot product between query and key a function of their relative position.
CoPE (Golovneva et al., 2024) computes context-dependent positions by applying a sigmoid gate to attention logits and cumulatively summing the gates. These fractional positions index into a learned position embedding table via linear interpolation. The position-dependent bias is added to the attention logits. CoPE adds \(n_{q} \times n_{kv} \times d_\text{head} \times n_\text{pos\_max}\) parameters.
ALiBi (Press et al., 2022) adds a fixed linear bias \(m \cdot (i - j)\) to each attention logit, where \(m\) is a per-head slope drawn from a geometric series. ALiBi adds zero learnable parameters.
Implementation: Cope, Alibi, RopeTable.


